So many have experienced at least one of the 10 ACEs of trauma, the categories of physical/emotional abuse, neglect, and household dysfunction that lead to severe health and life challenges as adults:
* Physical abuse
* Sexual abuse
* Emotional abuse
* Physical neglect
* Emotional neglect
* Mental illness
* Divorce
* Substance abuse
* Violence against your mother
* Mental illness
* Having a relative who has been sent to jail or prison

Science is finally starting to find the correlation between one’s childhood and how it affects their mental, emotional and physical health as an adult. More than ever, we can better understand how your brain and nervous system are affected by these experiences.

After working through years of my healing process with much progress, I went to a fantastic week-long retreat at @onsiteworkshops where I learned about the Adverse Childhood Experiences study. 

The data they found shows that the higher you “score” on the ACE’s test, the more likely you are to experience health issues like depression, cancer, and heart disease. It makes sense, but now the statistics help us understand how to get to the root of our health and life issues!

When I talk about beating the statistics and choosing your destiny over settling for fate and “your lot in life”- consciously healing your inner child is one of the integral ways to do that and that’s why I want to help with my work.

Let me be clear for anyone triggered by this kind of information; Facing, recognizing, and then naming what you have been through is the beginning of the healing process and is how we end cycles such as these. There is no going around that. It’s not always pretty, but it’s not as scary as many fear.

It’s not about blaming our parents or even our culture; they, too, are a part of a cycle. It’s about each of us collectively doing what only we can do, taking the responsibility to￼ heal ourselves.

Two great metaphors that are helpful to remember when struggling to meditate are:

See your thoughts like clouds and watch them come and go. No need to make them go away, just witness them and the shapes they take.

Feel emotions and sensory sensations like waves washing on sand. Sometimes their strong, sometime soft but they eventually change and move.

#Meditation is hands-down one of the best tools you can have in your tool kit for thriving in life.

Sometimes it’s hard for me to realize that I’m resisting grief. 

Acknowledging my grief looks like being present to the fact that there were things in life that I desperately wanted and did not get. Feeling into how things are, despite how badly I want them to be different.

Now that I think about it, it seems that resisting grief is actually being in denial.

The good news is, while we can't always change our circumstances; we can change our relationship with changes in our lives. 

When we allow ourselves to acknowledge and feel through what is no longer, we make space for what can be.

How does this hit like for you? Did anyone else need to hear this?

Want to know one of my big lessons this year!?

It’s not just who you spend time with but how you’re aligning with your ideal values, habits, and worldview!

I’m really asking…

Let me be clear… I’m not talking about cutting people off, being heartless or acting “better than”. I’m talking about getting clear on what we value, prioritize and see our lives so that we can be in integrity with that for ourselves FIRST.

Do you ever catch yourself when your taking something REALLY hard and wonder why?

Like you feel gutted when someone you didn’t like that much tells you they just want to be friends. Or go I to a deep overwhelm when something didn’t work out?!

We often don’t see it, but the holidays are the peak szn for healing ourselves and our relationships w/ parents and family. This time of year, we get an extra boost of energy from the wounded inner child’s unfinished business, which rises to help us see what we’ve left for our own adult reparenting. 

Because becoming aware of our old family dynamics can be so triggering for our yet-to-be-healed inner child, it’s essential to be mindful and patient with ourselves and others.

Shame, guilt, and blame often emerge when working through grief. If we keep moving through the grief process, anger arises to support us in making changes. When we stay mindful through this process, we can move through anger and arrive at acceptance and integration.

It’s important to note that your inner child work can be triggering for your parents and family, even if you’ve never spoken about your new needs or boundaries, they may feel shame and even angry that the once-assumed agreements are different. 

I often observe that some who have not done their inner child healing can be triggered by someone going through their healing process. It’s understandable when we’ve been in pain for so long- we tend to be very critical of the messy process of healing and reconnecting with our wounded parts.

This is why doing our healing is SO essential; it not only helps us to feel better, it supports us in having healthy and kind communication to change patterns that are no longer working.

Is this message for you? Do you often ask, “did I do something wrong?” when you thought everything was great just a moment before?

It took me a long time to realize that when this becomes obsessive behavior, it is codependency at work. 

It’s a sneaky trap that keeps you focused on prioritizing and manipulating the emotional experience of others. It’s often about a need for control when subconsciously, it’s likely a habit formed early in our childhood to help us navigate chaotic and emotionally unsafe situations and relationships.

When you become obsessive and harshly critical rather than thoughtful and mindful (which is light and neutral) after a social interaction that you feel uncomfortable about, it’s often a red flag that you’re triggered and caretaking for others before yourself.

This is a great time to stop and feel how you feel when you notice your obsessive thoughts.  Shift your focus from them and their feelings to feel you and YOUR feelings.

I find this is rarely about the other person or whether we “met the mark” or not… when we cross into painful obsessive overanalyzing of social interactions, I find that there is something in our subconscious that wants to be seen and heard… often a fear that we aren’t aware of.

So often, we have stories about what facial expressions, texts, or even silence means when the truth is it’s RARELY personal or about us. 

I also find that codependent behaviors tend to attract codependent responses in our relationships if both are unaware of their codependent tendencies. This can be on a broad spectrum, and not everyone struggles with this, but I find it’s more common than most people realize.

So much to work to on this. Tell me, is any of this true for you?

The key to new goals that stick is a new identity. 

Your beliefs and how they express themselves in your daily habits solidify your identity.

For example: Rather than being a non-smoker, you’re a person who doesn't smoke.

Want to work out in the new year? Start with changing your identity to being a fit person who works out three times a week, for starters. With this new identity held long enough, you'll start to create a lifestyle that supports who you’re becoming.

Unsure how to make this switch? 

1st, Read @jamesclear posts, who wrote a book called Atomic Habits that will help lay this whole concept out!

When we start to understand that this part of us is always there and that, like any child, the little you within has fears, worries, and opinions that need your attention. When those needs aren't met, your inner child will act out and cause pain out of confusion, fear, and neglect. 

But we can start to help ourselves by nurturing and parenting that part of ourselves by checking in, asking questions, and listening when things feel off.

If you were never taught how to have a healthy relationship and never learned how to communicate your needs... Your wounded inner child is likely showing up in adult relationships in ways that feel out of control.

The good news is, like any young one, your inner child just wants love and support on how to navigate this world.

Let’s talk about roles in a dysfunctional family, so you know not perpetuate them any longer. The first step is awareness around how unhealthy family roles work.

scape•goat scapegoat | ‘skäp,göt |
A person who is blamed for the wrongdoings, mistakes, or faults of others, especially for reasons of expediency.

In family units where a parent or caregiver has narcissistic personality disorder (NPD), there’s typically a family “scapegoat” — a person the family blames for their problems as a means of deflecting attention from real conflict. - @psychcentralofficial

Other signs that you may be the scapegoat:
Feeling like the family “punching bag”

Over burdened with responsibilities that are for other family members to take on 

Feeling as though your achievements are never enough or repulsive to family

Constantly verbally abused and criticized

Often isolated and ganged up on

Understanding this family dynamic can help you to heal and transform this painful experience into a new experience of self-love and empowerment. Adults who have yet to recover from this role tend to take on the blame and shame of friends and family as though this is their lit in life. When we wake up to this, we can begin to grieve, create boundaries and let go of relationships that don’t align with our new found self love and respect. 

Siblings who were not the scapegoat can also have transformational recovery from the recognition of the four types of dysfunctional family roles.

There is much to say about how to begin the healing process to free yourself of this role in your family and adult relationships.

Any easy-to-use tool I recommend to anyone overwhelmed by anxiety or even having trouble sleeping at night try C.P.R. No, not the chest compressions. It stands for Confront. Process. Regulate. Try it today and feel the difference.

Confronting our reality as how we take back our power.

Processing our emotions and beliefs is how we become present and stop running from our past or fearing our projected future.

Regulating our nervous system is how we tell our brain that it’s safe to turn off survival mode so that we can think, rest and solve. 

We must get out of our fear mind (focusing on problems) and shift our mindset to solutions. Regulating into rest and digest state is how we do that. This comes from finding tools to RELAX.

I love #breathwork for regulating your brain and body. It also helps to see your life from a higher perspective to find better solutions and not repeat old patterns.

#Breathwork & #meditation is for you. It is found in every culture around the world. We all breathe, we just don’t all yet remember how to use our breath for healing and self-transformation.

Breathwork can help activate the parasympathetic nervous system, which tells your brain you’re safe and able to rest and digest. This tells your body it’s ok to slow the heart beat down and open up the mind to thoughts that go beyond surviving.

This state is one where we can get ideas, let things go and solve bigger challenges.

Our ancestors may have needed these tools to regulate their nervous systems after being chased by a bear or to push through battles. But the biggest innovations and healing come from applying these tools every day. Many of us today have the privilege that our ancestors did not, let’s use it.

The practice that I use activates what’s known as the parasympathetic system.

If you think of a paramedic bringing you back to life,  parasympathetic is bringing you out of your survival mode, out of fight or flight. 

So if we’re living in the sympathetic, which is fight or flight, we are constantly afraid, feeling like everything is urgent, that starts to deteriorate our bodies, our minds, and our relationships. Everything.

But when we get into the parasympathetic, we rest and digest. That’s when we start to see our life from a wider lens. So when you’re running away from a bear, for example, your mind and vision begin to zoom in on the exit. 

If you’re always living like that, you see life that way. When you do breathwork, it helps you to widen your vision. But also, with your eyes closed, you start to see your own life from a higher perspective.  Even the most traumatic events that someone has been through, you can make new meaning of that.

Let’s say you had a car accident. You might have all these stories about how scary that was, which is real.  But if you start to reprocess them through a practice like breath work, you can now have new meanings. That car accident woke me up out of my relationship, which was unhealthy, and that car accident helped me see how fast in life I was going and how I needed to slow it down.

That’s what #breathwork can do. You start to change how you see yourself, your life, and the world. And that’s why breath work is so important for #trauma.

For those of you interested in the research: The study, “Health throughout the lifespan: The phenomenon of the inner child reflected in events during childhood experienced by older persons” conducted by Margareta Sjöblom, Kerstin Öhrling, Maria Prellwitz, and Catrine Kostenius of @luleauniversityoftechnology explores the concept of the “inner child” and its impact on the health and well-being of older individuals. The researchers investigate how events and experiences during childhood can continue to influence a person’s psychological and physical health later in life.

Through their research, the authors suggest that acknowledging and addressing the inner child can be a valuable approach in promoting the health and well-being of older individuals.

By investigating the connection between childhood experiences and well-being, the researchers emphasized the significance of addressing and understanding the impact of these experiences on psychological and physical health throughout the lifespan. Recognizing and processing unresolved emotions and memories from childhood may provide opportunities for improving overall health and well-being in later life.

Do you know the difference between shame and guilt!?

Shame vs. Guilt: Understanding the Difference 👇🏽
Shame is the belief that we are fundamentally flawed, while guilt stems from recognizing specific wrongdoings.

Shame: Shame is often rooted in early childhood experiences, where one may have experienced criticism, rejection, or abuse. It can also be influenced by cultural or societal expectations and agreements.

Guilt: Guilt arises from the awareness of having violated other or our own personal values, moral principles, or social norms. It is typically linked to a specific event or action.

Shame focuses on you, leading to self-condemnation and isolation, while guilt directs attention to our actions.

Healing shame involves developing self-compassion, challenging negative self-beliefs, and cultivating a sense of worthiness and self-acceptance.

Guilt can serve as a catalyst for positive change, shame hinders personal growth if not transformed by love and acceptance.

Let’s transform shame into self-compassion and use healthy guilt as a moral compass for growth and correction.

Healing ourselves is the process of rediscovering our innate wholeness. Not fixing ourselves or being “problem” free. 

Know as original mind in Zen Buddhism, Christ consciousness in mystical Christianity, and the true Self in modern spirituality. This idea of this deeper Self, doesn’t negate science or religion, it includes it.

It transcends conditioning, ego, time, and the illusions of separation and fear. However, many of us suffer from amnesia, forgetting who we really are. Only identifying with our ego, cultural and familial conditioning, jobs, and past experiences. Unbeknownst to us, this is what causes us pain.

Like the innocence of a baby upon birth, you are already whole. Nothing is missing or wrong with you. Wholeness is who you are. The opposite of being whole is not brokenness or separation but illusion. 

No matter what religion or family background, you were likely taught only about the human condition side of who you are; flawed, fearful, but evolving. 

An infant might be born with complications or pre-existing conditions, but it is no less pure, deserving of love, or full of possibility. When we look at human and animal babies, we understand their perfection and wholeness. When we see children who are free to explore the formless creative power within them, we call them genius. But what if all of us have that potential inside? 

Unfortunately, most of us were trained otherwise and forget that same intrinsic quality of ourselves. Healing, therefore, is the (re-) remembering of your true nature. And healing yourself is the process of returning to that wholeness. Healing ourselves is the journey of returning home to yourself.
